    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="indent(2)">To</p>
            <p>the <addressee> Reverend I. Leeser</addressee></p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">at</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">
                <hi rend="underline">
                    <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
                </hi>
            </p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>to the Reverend</p>
            <p><addressee>Dr. I. Leeser</addressee>.</p>
            <p>at <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>.</p>
            <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Hague</placeName>, the <date>17 Mai 57</date>.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Dear Sir,</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I have to repent<add>?</add> my sincere thanks for receiving<lb/>
                now regularly the <hi rend="underline">Occident</hi> that valuable paper
                furnishes<lb/> me every time great satisfaction. I have send you last you some<lb/>
                <add>?</add> from <placeName>Europe</placeName>, however I have not found them
                noticed or<lb/>
                <add>?</add>. Did you receive them?</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I <sic>heare</sic> with pleasure good tiding from my
                    <sic>freind</sic><lb/>
                <persName>d'Arcona</persName> and his family. God has given them now prosperity<lb/>
                and happiness after a great deal of suffering here. May that<lb/> prosperous state
                continue.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Did you read in the number of <date>15 Oct</date>. last of the<lb/>
                <hi rend="underline">Revue des Deme Mandes<add>?</add></hi> a very clever article on
                Jewish<lb/> affairs by a Frenchman, <persName>M. Erqinros<add>?</add></persName>?
                There are some misgivings<lb/> in that paper, however generally <sic>speaken</sic>
                the spirit is as generous<lb/> as the facts true. Perhaps you may give us some
                extracts<lb/> of that publication, the more as therein is spoken about the<lb/>
                American Jews <sic>allso</sic>.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I did converse last week with an Israelite of<lb/> reputation, the
                celebrated <persName>Benjamin II</persName>, a Jewish <sic>traveller</sic><lb/> who
                has made exploration five years long in the <placeName>far East</placeName>,<lb/> in
                    <placeName>Egypt</placeName>, and on the Barbarian shores, to elucidate the<lb/>
                situation of Jewish communities, Jewish history &amp; He has published<lb/> a work
                in French, <hi rend="underline"><add>?</add> Années de Voyage en
                        <placeName>Orient</placeName></hi>, wherein<lb/> he consigned the first
                results of his <hi rend="underline"><sic>remarquable</sic> voyage</hi>.<lb/> He
                intended now to go to the <placeName>Indian Archipelago</placeName>, then<lb/> to
                    <add>?</add> Indian and, if possible, crossing
                <placeName>Cabaal</placeName><lb/> and <placeName>Afghanistan</placeName> to return
                by these <sic>remoted</sic><lb/> Oriental countries. Our government has given him
                already<lb/> the necessary permission to set out for <placeName>Batavia</placeName>.
                If he<lb/> has completed his Oriental explorations, he may<lb/> perhaps visit your
                country and <placeName>America</placeName> in general. If you,<lb/> Sir, did not
                read still his voyage, I will</p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>to the utmost to procure it you.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">As for other publications about Jewish affairs<lb/> in
                    <placeName>Holland</placeName>, I have to <add>?</add> first the <hi
                    rend="underline">Jaarboekje</hi>, or<lb/> Ter. Annual for <del>Israelites</del>
                <date>1857</date>, being the 7th year. It had<lb/> again some valuable papers, and
                poetry of note. <persName>M. Mulder</persName><lb/> has contributed a very clever
                biographical sketch<lb/> of <persName>Johan Reuchlin</persName>, the human and
                learned <sic>protestor</sic><lb/> of the Jews in <placeName>Germany</placeName> in
                the <date>15th</date> and <date>16th ages</date>; <persName>Mr.<lb/>
                    Bortel</persName>, Historical and letter, miscellaneous. Further<lb/> deserves
                notice a biography of <persName>Benjamin Haas</persName>,<lb/> a Jewish (student at
                the <placeName>Leyden</placeName> university, who died last year);<lb/> the great
                particularity in his life was, he being unhappily<lb/> struck with blindness, he
                continued his classical<lb/>
                <sic>carreer</sic> and by the aid of friends and otherwise<lb/> he was amazed the
                first students of the university<lb/> his <sic>dead</sic> was very severely lamented
                by his parents,<lb/> his friends and professors. <persName>M. de Sola</persName>, at
                    <placeName>London</placeName><lb/> has contributed here some hebraical poetry,
                that<lb/> has been translated in Dutch verse. The young<lb/> Sr.<add>?</add>
                    poetreiss<add>?</add>, <add>?</add>
                <persName>Estella Vertzueld</persName>, has<lb/> adorned this annual with a very
                beautiful production,<lb/>
                <hi rend="underline">het Gebed</hi> (the Prayer), a production of a high minded<lb/>
                high <sic>inspirated</sic> and deep feeling young maid.
                    <persName>Delaville</persName>,<lb/> docent at the <add>?</add> seminarium at
                    <placeName>Amsterdam</placeName>, has published<lb/>
                <del>afterwards</del> last days a beautiful hebraic translation of it.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)"><persName>M. Lutomirsky</persName>, a great hebraissant
                    <sic>allso</sic><lb/> at <placeName>Rotterdam</placeName>, has published a Dutch
                and the br.<lb/> Prayerbook and <del>has</del> dedicated it to <persName>Miss
                    Estella Hertzued</persName>;<lb/>
                <del>who the</del> a younger sister of that poetress; <persName>Maria</persName>, is
                also a <add>?</add><lb/> in prose, of great promise.</p>
            <pb n="4"/>
            <p rend="indent(1)">From a parliamentary paper we extract the following<lb/> exact
                statistics concerning the Jewish population in the<lb/> American possessions of the
                    <placeName>Netherlands</placeName> (on <date>31 Dec. 1855</date>).</p>
            <table cols="4" rows="4">
                <row>
                    <cell>
                        <placeName>Suriname</placeName>
                    </cell>
                    <cell>1412</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <placeName>St. Eustache</placeName>
                    </cell>
                    <cell>3</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>
                        <placeName>Curaçao</placeName>
                    </cell>
                    <cell>747</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <placeName>St. Martin</placeName>
                    </cell>
                    <cell>1</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>
                        <placeName>Bun-Aire</placeName>
                    </cell>
                    <cell>1</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <hi rend="underline">
                            <placeName>Saba</placeName>
                        </hi>
                    </cell>
                    <cell>
                        <hi rend="underline">11</hi>
                    </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>
                        <placeName>Aruba</placeName>
                    </cell>
                    <cell>1</cell>
                    <cell>Total</cell>
                    <cell>2,165.</cell>
                </row>
            </table>
            <p rend="indent(1)">The <sic>Portugese</sic> Jews community in
                    <placeName>Suriname</placeName> counts<lb/> 675 members; the German Jews
                737.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">The Government has approved the election of<lb/> the rabbinical
                aspirant <persName>M. Lewenstein</persName>, who will<lb/> be chief rabbin for the
                two communities at <placeName>Suriname</placeName>.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I believe these particulars will interest<lb/> you, and I hope being
                able to forward to you, sir<lb/> very soon, other particulars. If you publish them,
                you<lb/> will give you the trouble to make the necessary corrections,<lb/> the
                English not being my mother tongue.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I take the liberty in one of my preceding<lb/> letters to ask you
                some particulars about <persName>M. de<lb/> Silva Solis</persName>, who
                    <sic>dead</sic> some years ago; he was, I believe,<lb/> a far relation of mine.
                If possible, write me something<lb/> about him and my family at
                    <placeName>Jamaica</placeName>; it is but family interest<lb/> that induces me
                to give you that trouble.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Dispose with all liberty on me, here, and<lb/> agree, sir, the
                assurance of my deeprooted feelings on your<lb/> part; so believe me, your humble
                and most obedient servant,</p>
            <p rend="indent(6)">
                <persName role="author">J.J. Belinfante</persName>
            </p>
        </body>
